# ADR-0009 — Workflow Execution Model

- Status: Accepted
- Date: 2026-07-19
- Deciders: Pharos Architecture Team

---

# Context

The Runtime separates planning from execution.

After a RuntimeIntent is analyzed by the RuntimePlanner, the result is
represented as a RuntimePlan.

A design decision was required:

Should RuntimePlan execute itself?

Or should execution be delegated to another abstraction?

The second approach was selected.

---

# Decision

RuntimePlan is a pure data structure.

Execution is delegated to Workflow.

Workflow instances are constructed by WorkflowBuilder.

```
RuntimeIntent
        │
        ▼
RuntimePlanner
        │
        ▼
RuntimePlan
        │
        ▼
WorkflowBuilder
        │
        ▼
Workflow
        │
        ▼
WorkflowResult
```

Planning and execution are independent responsibilities.

---

# Why RuntimePlan Is Not Executable

A RuntimePlan answers:

> What should happen?

It never answers:

> How should it happen?

Examples of RuntimePlan data:

- goals
- ordered steps
- dependencies
- constraints
- metadata

A RuntimePlan contains no execution logic.

---

# Why Workflow Exists

Workflow represents executable behaviour.

It owns:

- execution order
- execution lifecycle
- step progression
- future cancellation
- future retries
- future parallel execution
- future monitoring

Workflow is behaviour.

RuntimePlan is data.

---

# WorkflowBuilder

WorkflowBuilder converts a RuntimePlan into an executable Workflow.

It owns no planning logic.

It owns no execution.

It only assembles execution.

Different builders may produce different workflows for the same plan.

Examples:

```
RuntimePlan

↓

SequentialWorkflow
```

```
RuntimePlan

↓

ParallelWorkflow
```

```
RuntimePlan

↓

DistributedWorkflow
```

The planner remains unchanged.

---

# Current Implementation

Current Runtime uses:

```
DefaultWorkflowBuilder

↓

MinimalWorkflow
```

MinimalWorkflow exists only to provide a deterministic Runtime bootstrap.

It performs no orchestration.

It simply returns a WorkflowResult.

Future implementations will replace it without changing RuntimeEngine.

---

# Dependency Rules

Workflow depends on:

- RuntimePlan (through construction)

Workflow never depends on:

- RuntimePlanner
- RuntimeIntent
- Company
- Products

WorkflowBuilder depends only on:

- RuntimePlan
- Workflow contracts

---

# Architectural Principles

## Data vs Behaviour

RuntimePlan stores information.

Workflow performs work.

The two concepts must never be merged.

---

## Replaceable Execution

Execution models may evolve independently.

Possible future workflows:

- SequentialWorkflow
- ParallelWorkflow
- ConditionalWorkflow
- RetryWorkflow
- StreamingWorkflow
- MultiAgentWorkflow

No planner changes are required.

---

## Stable Planning Layer

Planning is isolated from execution.

Improving execution never changes planners.

Improving planners never changes execution.

---

# Alternatives Considered

## RuntimePlan executes itself

Rejected.

Data objects should not own execution behaviour.

---

## RuntimePlanner executes directly

Rejected.

Planning and execution have different responsibilities.

---

## RuntimeEngine executes RuntimePlan

Rejected.

RuntimeEngine coordinates.

Workflow executes.

---

# Consequences

Positive:

- strict separation of concerns
- replaceable execution models
- simpler planners
- cleaner testing
- future orchestration support

Negative:

- one additional abstraction
- slightly more architectural complexity

The benefits outweigh the additional abstraction.

---

# Future Evolution

Future Workflow implementations may support:

- retries
- cancellation
- pause / resume
- checkpointing
- streaming
- metrics
- distributed execution
- multi-agent execution

The Runtime Core remains unchanged.

